  "opinion": "As a mechanic in Bari with a bachelor’s degree and a background in practical, hands-on work, I’ve seen how science and engineering can be both deeply useful and deeply misunderstood by those who don’t engage with it directly. The gender gap in science isn’t just a statistical curiosity—it’s a real-world issue that affects who gets to build the tools that keep our lives running smoothly. For me, it’s about how we talk about science, not just the numbers. In my shop, I’ve noticed that many young people, especially girls, feel intimidated by the technical language and the idea of ‘science’ as something only for boys. That’s why I think addressing the gap isn’t about pushing for more women into labs—it’s about making science feel relevant and accessible to everyone. I’ve seen it in my own community: when I talk to kids in my neighborhood about fixing cars or understanding how engines work, I avoid jargon and focus on real problems. If we can show science as a practical skill, not an abstract theory, then it becomes something anyone can approach. As a man who’s lived through the transition from my parents’ generation to today’s world, I’ve seen how education systems often overlook the practical applications of science. That’s why I believe the solution starts with teachers and parents who can connect science to everyday life. For example, in Bari, where I’ve worked for decades, we could integrate more hands-on projects into schools, like building simple machines or understanding electricity through everyday devices. This approach would make science feel less intimidating and more like a tool for solving real problems. The gender gap in science shouldn’t be a barrier—it should be an opportunity to rethink how we teach and engage with science in a way that includes everyone.",
